<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="760" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="8.[491,1556,229,1911]" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[531,654,955,979]" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">Etymology</emphasis>
— “ 
<taxonomicName authority="(Latin)" authorityName="Pešić &amp; Jovanović &amp; Ana &amp; Manović &amp; Zawal &amp; Bańkowska &amp; Broda &amp; Martin &amp; Dabert" authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="Latin" box="[705,788,955,979]" class="Arachnida" family="Hygrobatidae" genus="Hygrobates" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="760" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lacrima">
<emphasis box="[705,788,955,979]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">lacrima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” (Latin): tear, in reference to the name of Tara River – The Tear of Europe.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="760" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="8.[491,1556,229,1911]" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[531,634,1024,1048]" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">Remarks</emphasis>
— Based on molecular analysis, 
<taxonomicName authority="Pešić &amp; Jovanović &amp; Ana &amp; Manović &amp; Zawal &amp; Bańkowska &amp; Broda &amp; Martin &amp; Dabert, 2020" authorityName="Pešić &amp; Jovanović &amp; Ana &amp; Manović &amp; Zawal &amp; Bańkowska &amp; Broda &amp; Martin &amp; Dabert" authorityYear="2020" box="[993,1206,1024,1048]" class="Arachnida" family="Hygrobatidae" genus="Hygrobates" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="760" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lacrima" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[993,1206,1024,1048]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">Hygrobates lacrima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1213,1302,1024,1048]" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1213,1302,1024,1048]" pageId="8" pageNumber="760" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is closely related to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lebert" authorityYear="1879" box="[519,717,1058,1082]" class="Arachnida" family="Hygrobatidae" genus="Hygrobates" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="760" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigromaculatus">
<emphasis box="[519,717,1058,1082]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">H. nigromaculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The distance between these two species was 15.87% (
<collectingRegion box="[1308,1343,1058,1082]" country="Serbia" name="Sid" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">SD</collectingRegion>
= 1.74) K 
<specimenCount box="[1445,1475,1058,1082]" pageId="8" pageNumber="760" type="generic">2P.</specimenCount>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[491,1556,229,1911]" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">
In comparison with the new species from 
<collectingCountry box="[980,1113,1094,1118]" name="Serbia" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">Montenegro</collectingCountry>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lebert" authorityYear="1879" box="[1117,1315,1093,1117]" class="Arachnida" family="Hygrobatidae" genus="Hygrobates" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="760" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigromaculatus">
<emphasis box="[1117,1315,1093,1117]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">H. nigromaculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(data taken from 
<bibRefCitation author="Martin P. &amp; Dabert M. &amp; Dabert J." box="[491,690,1127,1151]" pageId="8" pageNumber="760" pagination="347 - 360" refId="ref8241" refString="Martin P., Dabert M., Dabert J. 2010. Molecular evidence for species separation in the water mite Hygrobates nigromaculatus Lebert, 1879 (Acari, Hydrachnidia): evolutionary consequences of the loss of larval parasitism. Aquat. Sci., 72: 347 - 360. doi: 10.1007 / s 00027 - 010 - 0135 - x" type="journal article" year="2010">
Martin 
<emphasis box="[572,627,1127,1151]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">et al.</emphasis>
2010
</bibRefCitation>
) generally is smaller in dimensions. In males of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lebert" authorityYear="1879" box="[1228,1427,1127,1151]" class="Arachnida" family="Hygrobatidae" genus="Hygrobates" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="760" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigromaculatus">
<emphasis box="[1228,1427,1127,1151]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">H. nigromaculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the length of genital plate is ˂ 160 
<emphasis box="[835,857,1163,1186]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">vs</emphasis>
(. ˃ 220 μm in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pešić &amp; Jovanović &amp; Ana &amp; Manović &amp; Zawal &amp; Bańkowska &amp; Broda &amp; Martin &amp; Dabert" authorityYear="2020" box="[1013,1129,1162,1186]" class="Arachnida" family="Hygrobatidae" genus="Hygrobates" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="760" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lacrima">
<emphasis box="[1013,1129,1162,1186]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">H. lacrima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), in females ˂ 175 (
<emphasis box="[1346,1368,1163,1186]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">vs</emphasis>
. ˃ 210 μm
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[491,1556,229,1911]" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">
in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pešić &amp; Jovanović &amp; Ana &amp; Manović &amp; Zawal &amp; Bańkowska &amp; Broda &amp; Martin &amp; Dabert" authorityYear="2020" box="[520,637,1196,1220]" class="Arachnida" family="Hygrobatidae" genus="Hygrobates" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="760" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lacrima">
<emphasis box="[520,637,1196,1220]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">H. lacrima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); mL Cx-I + gnathosoma in males is ˂ 280 (
<emphasis box="[1128,1150,1197,1220]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">vs</emphasis>
. ˃ 340 μm in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pešić &amp; Jovanović &amp; Ana &amp; Manović &amp; Zawal &amp; Bańkowska &amp; Broda &amp; Martin &amp; Dabert" authorityYear="2020" box="[1312,1429,1196,1220]" class="Arachnida" family="Hygrobatidae" genus="Hygrobates" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="760" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lacrima">
<emphasis box="[1312,1429,1196,1220]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">H. lacrima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), in females ˂ 350 μm (
<emphasis box="[700,722,1232,1255]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">vs</emphasis>
. ˃ 340 μm in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pešić &amp; Jovanović &amp; Ana &amp; Manović &amp; Zawal &amp; Bańkowska &amp; Broda &amp; Martin &amp; Dabert" authorityYear="2020" box="[876,991,1231,1255]" class="Arachnida" family="Hygrobatidae" genus="Hygrobates" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="760" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lacrima">
<emphasis box="[876,991,1231,1255]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">H. lacrima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); the length of P- 
<quantity box="[1191,1232,1231,1255]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.016" pageId="8" pageNumber="760" unit="in" value="4.0">4 in</quantity>
males 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lebert" authorityYear="1879" box="[1296,1494,1231,1255]" class="Arachnida" family="Hygrobatidae" genus="Hygrobates" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="760" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigromaculatus">
<emphasis box="[1296,1494,1231,1255]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">H. nigromaculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is ˂ 130 (
<emphasis box="[597,619,1267,1290]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">vs</emphasis>
. ˃ 160 μm in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pešić &amp; Jovanović &amp; Ana &amp; Manović &amp; Zawal &amp; Bańkowska &amp; Broda &amp; Martin &amp; Dabert" authorityYear="2020" box="[781,898,1266,1290]" class="Arachnida" family="Hygrobatidae" genus="Hygrobates" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="760" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lacrima">
<emphasis box="[781,898,1266,1290]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">H. lacrima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), in females ˂ 165 μm (
<emphasis box="[1163,1185,1267,1290]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">vs</emphasis>
. ˃ 180 μm in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pešić &amp; Jovanović &amp; Ana &amp; Manović &amp; Zawal &amp; Bańkowska &amp; Broda &amp; Martin &amp; Dabert" authorityYear="2020" box="[1347,1464,1266,1290]" class="Arachnida" family="Hygrobatidae" genus="Hygrobates" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="760" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lacrima">
<emphasis box="[1347,1464,1266,1290]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">H. lacrima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Moreover, the species live in different habitats: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lebert" authorityYear="1879" box="[994,1192,1300,1324]" class="Arachnida" family="Hygrobatidae" genus="Hygrobates" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="760" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigromaculatus">
<emphasis box="[994,1192,1300,1324]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">H. nigromaculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in lakes, whereas 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pešić &amp; Jovanović &amp; Ana &amp; Manović &amp; Zawal &amp; Bańkowska &amp; Broda &amp; Martin &amp; Dabert" authorityYear="2020" box="[1383,1497,1300,1324]" class="Arachnida" family="Hygrobatidae" genus="Hygrobates" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="760" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lacrima">
<emphasis box="[1383,1497,1300,1324]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">H. lacrima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
inhabits pools and shallow eddies along faster flowing waters (see 
<figureCitation box="[1261,1347,1335,1359]" captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="14.[119,186,1975,1996]" captionTargetBox="[193,1405,220,1921]" captionTargetId="figure-2@14.[193,1405,220,1921]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Figure 9 Sampling sites: A-B – River Tara near Trebaljevo; C – River Tara near Mateševo; D – the ”Kraljičino Oko” (the Queen’s Eye) spring near Podgorica; E – River Crni Drim near Struga; F – the Vitoja spring located on the north-eastern shore of Lake Skadar flooded in the winter and spring months." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5398633" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5398633/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">Figs. 9</figureCitation>
A-C). From 
<taxonomicName box="[1441,1467,1336,1359]" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">
<emphasis box="[1441,1467,1336,1359]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">H.</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[491,1556,229,1911]" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">
<emphasis box="[491,568,1370,1393]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">setosus</emphasis>
(in parentheses, based on material from Farver Au, 
<collectingCountry box="[1147,1250,1369,1393]" name="Germany" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">Germany</collectingCountry>
), male of new species differs in having the bluntly-pointed medial projection of the genital field and comparatively wider genital field (L/W ratio 0.83-0.9; compare 
<figureCitation box="[1016,1199,1438,1462]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="7.[119,186,1946,1967]" captionTargetBox="[236,1362,231,1888]" captionTargetId="figure-2@7.[231,1366,221,1891]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 5 Genital field: A-B –Hygrobates lacrima sp. nov., paratypes (A, ♂; B, ♀), Trebaljevo, Montenegro; C-F –Hygrobates limnocrenicus sp. nov. (C-D, F, ♀; E, ♂); C, holotype, Mareza, Montenegro; D, paratype, Struga, North Macedonia; E-F, Vitoja, Montenegro; G-HH –. setosus Besseling, 1942, ♂, G, Farver Au, Germany; H, redrawn from Besseling (1964)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5398623" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5398623/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">Fig. 5A and 5G</figureCitation>
). Although 
<bibRefCitation author="Tuzovskij, P. V." box="[1338,1509,1438,1462]" pageId="8" pageNumber="760" refId="ref9071" refString="Tuzovskij, P. V. 2017. On the systematic of the water mites Hygrobates nigromaculatus Lebert, 1879" type="book" year="2017">Tuzovskij (2017)</bibRefCitation>
showed different 
<typeStatus box="[691,747,1474,1498]" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">types</typeStatus>
of male genital plates for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lebert" authorityYear="1879" box="[1010,1209,1473,1497]" class="Arachnida" family="Hygrobatidae" genus="Hygrobates" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="760" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigromaculatus">
<emphasis box="[1010,1209,1473,1497]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">H. nigromaculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, we cannot exclude that he dealt with several species. Therefore, we think that the differences between the male genital plates of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pešić &amp; Jovanović &amp; Ana &amp; Manović &amp; Zawal &amp; Bańkowska &amp; Broda &amp; Martin &amp; Dabert" authorityYear="2020" box="[589,704,1542,1566]" class="Arachnida" family="Hygrobatidae" genus="Hygrobates" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="760" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lacrima">
<emphasis box="[589,704,1542,1566]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">H. lacrima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and other species as given in the key are justified.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[491,1556,229,1911]" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">
Due to its larger size and habitat preference for running waters, the new species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Pešić &amp; Jovanović &amp; Ana &amp; Manović &amp; Zawal &amp; Bańkowska &amp; Broda &amp; Martin &amp; Dabert, 2020" authorityName="Pešić &amp; Jovanović &amp; Ana &amp; Manović &amp; Zawal &amp; Bańkowska &amp; Broda &amp; Martin &amp; Dabert" authorityYear="2020" box="[519,701,1611,1635]" class="Arachnida" family="Hygrobatidae" genus="Hygrobates" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="760" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="limnocrenicus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[519,701,1611,1635]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">H. limnocrenicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[707,796,1611,1635]" pageId="8" pageNumber="760" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[707,789,1611,1635]" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">sp. nov</emphasis>
.
</taxonomicNameLabel>
(see there for further discussion).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="760" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="8.[491,1556,229,1911]" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[531,670,1646,1670]" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">Distribution</emphasis>
— 
<collectingCountry box="[709,848,1646,1670]" name="Serbia" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">Montenegro</collectingCountry>
; know from two localities along the middle course of the Tara River (
<figureCitation box="[565,643,1680,1704]" captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="14.[119,186,1975,1996]" captionTargetBox="[193,1405,220,1921]" captionTargetId="figure-2@14.[193,1405,220,1921]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Figure 9 Sampling sites: A-B – River Tara near Trebaljevo; C – River Tara near Mateševo; D – the ”Kraljičino Oko” (the Queen’s Eye) spring near Podgorica; E – River Crni Drim near Struga; F – the Vitoja spring located on the north-eastern shore of Lake Skadar flooded in the winter and spring months." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5398633" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5398633/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">Figs. 9</figureCitation>
A-C). These two sites were subject of a monthly monitoring survey in 2019 on the river biota of the Tara River during the Bar-Boljare highway development activities (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Pesic V. &amp; Grabowski M. &amp; Hadziablahovic S. &amp; Maric D. &amp; Paunovic M." pageId="8" pageNumber="760" refId="ref8766" refString="Pesic V., Grabowski M., Hadziablahovic S., Maric D., Paunovic M. 2020 a. The biodiversity and biogeographical characteristics of the River basins of Montenegro. In: Pesic V., Paunovic M., Kostianoy A. (Eds). The rivers of Montenegro. The handbook of environmental chemistry. Springer, Cham. doi: 10.1007 / 698 _ 2019 _ 414" type="book" year="2020">
Pešić 
<emphasis box="[491,545,1749,1773]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">et al.</emphasis>
2020a
</bibRefCitation>
). At the Mataševo site, only 
<specimenCount box="[921,1066,1749,1773]" pageId="8" pageNumber="760" type="generic">one specimen</specimenCount>
(which was successfully barcoded) was collected, probably due to the negative ecological impact associated with highway development activities in the immediate vicinity (for the controversy surrounding highway construction over the Tara River see 
<bibRefCitation author="Pesic V. &amp; Paunovic M. &amp; Kostianoy A. &amp; Pesic-Vukasinovic V." box="[693,881,1853,1877]" pageId="8" pageNumber="760" refId="ref8841" refString="Pesic V., Paunovic M., Kostianoy A., Pesic-Vukasinovic V. 2020 b. Rivers of Montenegro - from conflicts to science-based management. In: Pesic V., Paunovic M., Kostianoy A. (Eds). The rivers of Montenegro. The handbook of environmental chemistry. Springer, Cham. doi: 10.1007 / 698 _ 2020 _ 480" type="book" year="2020">
Pešić 
<emphasis box="[753,806,1853,1877]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="760">et al.</emphasis>
2020b
</bibRefCitation>
). At the Trebaljevo site located downstream, the negative impact was less pronounced - here, three individuals were collected.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
